        <span class="property-type">string</span>
    </dt>

See <a href="https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/storage/volumes/#emptydir">https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/storage/volumes/#emptydir</a> for details.</dd><dt class="property-optional"
            title="Optional">
        <span id="ephemeralvolumeclaimspec_yaml">
<a data-swiftype-name="resource-property" data-swiftype-type="text" href="#ephemeralvolumeclaimspec_yaml" style="color: inherit; text-decoration: inherit;">ephemeral<wbr>Volume<wbr>Claim<wbr>Spec</a>
</span>
        <span class="property-indicator"></span>
        <span class="property-type"><a href="#volumeclaimspecresponse">Property Map</a></span>
    </dt>
    <dd>Use the specified persistent volume claim template to mount a &quot;generic ephemeral volume&quot; for the message buffer. See <a href="https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/storage/ephemeral-volumes/#generic-ephemeral-volumes">https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/storage/ephemeral-volumes/#generic-ephemeral-volumes</a> for details.</dd><dt class="property-optional"
            title="Optional">
        <span id="persistentvolumeclaimspec_yaml">

</span>

        <span class="property-type"><a href="#volumeclaimspecresponse">Property Map</a></span>
    </dt>

<h4 id="volumeclaimspecresponse">Volume<wbr>Claim<wbr>Spec<wbr>Response</h4>



<div>
<pulumi-choosable type="language" values="csharp">

            title="Optional">

        <span class="property-indicator"></span>
        <span class="property-type">List&lt;string&gt;</span>

    <dd>AccessModes contains the desired access modes the volume should have. More info: https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/storage/persistent-volumes#access-modes-1</dd><dt class="property-optional"
            title="Optional">
        <span id="datasource_csharp">

        <span class="property-indicator"></span>
        <span class="property-type"><a href="#localkubernetesreferenceresponse">Pulumi.<wbr>Azure<wbr>Native.<wbr>Io<wbr>TOperations.<wbr>Inputs.<wbr>Local<wbr>Kubernetes<wbr>Reference<wbr>Response</a></span>
    </dt>
    <dd>This field can be used to specify either: * An existing VolumeSnapshot object (snapshot.storage.k8s.io/VolumeSnapshot) * An existing PVC (PersistentVolumeClaim) If the provisioner or an external controller can support the specified data source, it will create a new volume based on the contents of the specified data source.             title="Optional">
        <span id="datasourceref_csharp">
<a data-swiftype-name="resource-property" data-swiftype-type="text" href="#datasourceref_csharp" style="color: inherit; text-decoration: inherit;">Data<wbr>Source<wbr>Ref</a>
</span>
        <span class="property-indicator"></span>
        <span class="property-type"><a href="#kubernetesreferenceresponse">Pulumi.<wbr>Azure<wbr>Native.<wbr>Io<wbr>TOperations.<wbr>Inputs.<wbr>Kubernetes<wbr>Reference<wbr>Response</a></span>
    </dt>
    <dd>Specifies the object from which to populate the volume with data, if a non-empty volume is desired. This may be any local object from a non-empty API group (non core object) or a PersistentVolumeClaim object. When this field is specified, volume binding will only succeed if the type of the specified object matches some installed volume populator or dynamic provisioner. This field will replace the functionality of the DataSource field and as such if both fields are non-empty, they must have the same value. For backwards compatibility, both fields (DataSource and DataSourceRef) will be set to the same value automatically if one of them is empty and the other is non-empty. There are two important differences between DataSource and DataSourceRef: * While DataSource only allows two specific types of objects, DataSourceRef allows any non-core object, as well as PersistentVolumeClaim objects. * While DataSource ignores disallowed values (dropping them), DataSourceRef preserves all values, and generates an error if a disallowed value is specified. (Beta) Using this field requires the AnyVolumeDataSource feature gate to be enabled.</dd><dt class="property-optional"
            title="Optional">
        <span id="resources_csharp">
<a data-swiftype-name="resource-property" data-swiftype-type="text" href="#resources_csharp" style="color: inherit; text-decoration: inherit;">Resources</a>
</span>
        <span class="property-indicator"></span>
        <span class="property-type"><a href="#volumeclaimresourcerequirementsresponse">Pulumi.<wbr>Azure<wbr>Native.<wbr>Io<wbr>TOperations.<wbr>Inputs.<wbr>Volume<wbr>Claim<wbr>Resource<wbr>Requirements<wbr>Response</a></span>
    </dt>
    <dd>Resources represents the minimum resources the volume should have. If RecoverVolumeExpansionFailure feature is enabled users are allowed to specify resource requirements that are lower than previous value but must still be higher than capacity recorded in the status field of the claim. More info: https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/storage/persistent-volumes#resources</dd><dt class="property-optional"
            title="Optional">
        <span id="selector_csharp">

</span>
        <span class="property-indicator"></span>
        <span class="property-type"><a href="#volumeclaimspecselectorresponse">Pulumi.<wbr>Azure<wbr>Native.<wbr>Io<wbr>TOperations.<wbr>Inputs.<wbr>Volume<wbr>Claim<wbr>Spec<wbr>Selector<wbr>Response</a></span>
    </dt>
    <dd>A label query over volumes to consider for binding.</dd><dt class="property-optional"
            title="Optional">

This may be any local object from a non-empty API group (non core object) or a PersistentVolumeClaim object. When this field is specified, volume binding will only succeed if the type of the specified object matches some installed volume populator or dynamic provisioner. This field will replace the functionality of the DataSource field and as such if both fields are non-empty, they must have the same value. For backwards compatibility, both fields (DataSource and DataSourceRef) will be set to the same value automatically if one of them is empty and the other is non-empty. There are two important differences between DataSource and DataSourceRef: * While DataSource only allows two specific types of objects, DataSourceRef allows any non-core object, as well as PersistentVolumeClaim objects. * While DataSource ignores disallowed values (dropping them), DataSourceRef preserves all values, and generates an error if a disallowed value is specified. (Beta) Using this field requires the AnyVolumeDataSource feature gate to be enabled.</dd><dt class="property-optional"
